You are a senior frontend engineer building a production-ready MVP.



Build a Next.js (App Router) web application based strictly on the following constraints and requirements:



GENERAL RULES:

\- Use Next.js App Router

\- Do NOT create a separate backend or microservices

\- Do NOT use a database

\- Use Server Actions for form submissions

\- Store form submissions in Google Sheets using Google Sheets API

\- Workshop data must be hardcoded in the codebase (constants/config files)

\- Use Tailwind CSS

\- Do NOT over-engineer

\- This is an MVP landing + lead collection website



COMPONENT SOURCING RULES (CRITICAL):

\- \*\*DO NOT\*\* assume a pre-existing folder of components exists.

\- \*\*shadcn/ui:\*\* Use for foundational UI elements (Button, Input, Card, Form, Label, Textarea).

&nbsp; - You must advise on the CLI commands to install them (e.g., `npx shadcn@latest add button`).

\- \*\*ReactBits:\*\* Use for creative/interactive elements (Hero Animations, Carousel).

&nbsp; - You must generate these components files manually (e.g., `components/ui/FallingText.jsx`) by referencing the \*\*ReactBits documentation\*\* context (@ReactBits).

&nbsp; - Do not hallucinate imports; create the file content based on the docs.



DESIGN GUIDELINES:

\- Style should feel like a professional education platform

\- Target audience: parents of middle school students

\- Clean, trustworthy, modern

\- Not childish, not overly academic

\- Clear call-to-actions



PAGES TO BUILD:



1\. Home Page (/)

\- Hero section: Use a \*\*ReactBits\*\* animation component (e.g., Split Text or specialized Carousel).

&nbsp; - Autoplay enabled

&nbsp; - Dot navigation visible and clickable

\- Mission / Vision section: Use \*\*shadcn/ui\*\* Card or a grid layout.

\- Workshop list: Use \*\*shadcn/ui\*\* Cards.

&nbsp; - Data comes from a hardcoded workshops config

&nbsp; - Each workshop shows:

&nbsp; - Period name

&nbsp; - Date range

&nbsp; - Short description

&nbsp; - "Reserve Now" button (shadcn Button) linking to /rezervasyon

\- Strong CTA section linking to /iletisim



2\. Contact Page (/iletisim)

\- Simple contact form using \*\*shadcn/ui\*\* Form components:

&nbsp; - Name (Input)

&nbsp; - Phone (Input)

&nbsp; - Email (Input)

&nbsp; - Message (Textarea)

\- On submit:

&nbsp; - Use a Server Action

&nbsp; - Append a row to a Google Sheet

&nbsp; - Send a notification email to admin

&nbsp; - Show success message (use shadcn/ui Toast or Alert)



3\. Reservation Page (/rezervasyon)

\- Display available workshop periods and dates

\- Reservation form (survey-style) using \*\*shadcn/ui\*\*:

&nbsp; - Student age

&nbsp; - Student grade

&nbsp; - Parent name

&nbsp; - Phone

&nbsp; - Email

&nbsp; - Interest areas (shadcn Checkbox)

&nbsp; - Optional notes

\- Each workshop date maps to a DIFFERENT Google Sheet

\- On submit:

&nbsp; - Determine correct Sheet ID from selected workshop

&nbsp; - Append row using Server Action

&nbsp; - Send admin email



SECURITY:

\- Basic client-side validation (Zod + React Hook Form standard in shadcn)

\- Server-side validation

\- Honeypot field

\- Basic rate limiting



ARCHITECTURE:

\- Keep folder structure clean and simple

\- `components/ui` -> for shadcn and ReactBits components

\- `lib` -> for utils and google sheets logic

\- `app` -> for routes

\- Use constants for workshop data and sheet ID mapping

\- Use environment variables for Google credentials


ENVIRONMENT & TERMINAL:
- User OS: Windows 11 (WSL2 - Ubuntu/Debian)
- Terminal Shell: Bash / Zsh
- CLI Syntax: Always use Linux commands (e.g., `ls`, `rm -rf`, `export`), NEVER use PowerShell or cmd.exe commands (e.g., `dir`, `del`, `set`).
- Package Manager: pnpm (run within WSL)


OUTPUT EXPECTATION:

\- Clean, readable, maintainable code

\- No unnecessary abstractions

\- Explain briefly what you are doing when needed, but focus on code



Start by proposing the folder structure, then implement page by page.

